<html>
<body>

<center>
<b>PREPARE SLR DATA HANDLING FILE</b>
<p>Program: SNX2SLR
</center>
<hr width="100%">

<a name="ENVIRONMENT"   default="%% %%"></a>
<a name="CAMPAIGN"      default=""></a>
<a name="SESSION_TABLE" default="SESSIONS"></a>
<a name="YR4_INFO"      default="$Y+0"></a>
<a name="SES_INFO"      default="$S+0"></a>
<a name="USR_INFO"      default="${USER}"></a>

<p><b>GENERAL DESCRIPTION</b>
<p>
The purpose of the program SNX2SLR is to prepare a file containing the
SLR data handling information. This comprises:
<ul>
<li>A priori range biases to be considered.
<li>Center-of-mass corrections for spherical satellites.
</ul>
The information can be extracted either from a SINEX file
(e.g. the official data handling file provided by the ILRS)
or from a previously generated Bernese-formatted SLR data handling file.
<br>
A second Bernese-formatted SLR data handling file can be merged into the
resulting file. This is especially needed for merging information on
range biases with the center-of-mass values into one file.
<br>
Additionally, a station information file containing station exclusions
can be written.
This information must come from the input SINEX file.
Only exclusion intervals larger than 1 day are considered.

<p><hr>

<p><b>SNX2SLR 1: Filenames</b>

<a name="SHOWGEN" default="1"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL FILES</b>
<p><b>Show all general files:</b>
Check this box to get the currently active campaign, session and session table.

<br><br>

<a name="SNXFILE" default=""></a>
<a name="SLRFIL1" default=""></a>
<p><b>INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Master file:</b>
Selection of a master file. All data handling information from the master file
will be taken over to the new file. The content
of the master file will not be changed in any way.
Only entries of the merge file which are not contained in the master file
will be added.
<br>
The master file can be in SINEX format (e.g. official ILRS files)
or in the Bernese-formatted SLR data handling file
(<a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.SLR">Example</a>).

<a name="SLRFIL2" default=""></a>
<p><b>Merge file:</b>
A Bernese-formatted SLR data handling file to be merged into one resulting
SLR data handling file
(<a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.SLR">Example</a>).
The content of this merged set is only written into the resulting file if the
entry is not present in the "Master file".

<br><br>

<a name="SLR_OUT" default=""></a>
<p><b>OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>SLR data handling file:</b>
Name of resulting Bernese-formatted SLR data handling file.

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.SLR">Example</a>

<a name="STAFILE" default=""></a>
<p><b>Station information file:</b>
Name of resulting Station information file containing exclusions of stations
for specific intervals (according to the information given in the SINEX
master input file).

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.STA">Example</a>

<br><br>

<a name="SYSODEF" default="1"></a>
<a name="SYSOUT"  default="SNX2SLR"></a>
<p><b>GENERAL OUTPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>Program output:</b>
You can choose to have the program output written to a separate file for each
program run (checkbox marked), or specify a common name for all program runs.
<br>
If you mark the checkbox, the filename will correspond to the program name
with an extension containing a counter (Lnn), which is automatically
incremented for each program run. If the counter reaches the maximum value, it
is automatically reset, and existing files will be overwritten.
The maximum value can be set in
<b>Menu &gt; Configure &gt; Program Names</b>, option "Maximum program output
file number".
<br>
If the checkbox is unmarked, you have to specify a name for the program
output file. This allows to characterize the program run, e.g., by using the
day and year (<tt>$YD+0</tt>) in the filename.

<a name="ERRMRG" default="0"></a>
<a name="SYSERR" default="ERROR"></a>
<p><b>Error messages:</b>
You can choose to have error messages written into the program's output
file (see above), or to specify a separate file to which error messages are
written.

<p><hr>

<p><b>SNX2SLR 1.1: General Files</b>

<a name="CONST" default="CONST."></a>
<p><b>GENERAL INPUT FILES</b>
<p><b>General constants:</b>
This file contains all the physical and astronomical constants used
in the Bernese GNSS Software. Most probably you will never have to
modify this file.

<p>Example: <a href="/$X/GEN/CONST.">$X/GEN/CONST.</a>

<p><hr>

<p><b>SNX2SLR 2: Settings</b>

<a name="TITLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>TITLE</b>
<p>
This title line will be printed as header comment into the program output
to document the program run. The title should characterize the program run by,
e.g., giving the most important options used and the session.

<a name="MININTE" default="1"></a>
<p><b>OPTIONS</b>
<p><b>Minimum number of days for station exclusions:</b>
You can specify here the minimum day interval for station exclusion.
If the chosen value is 0, then all exclusions will be stored in the Station
information file.
Otherwise only those exclusions will be saved, for which the time interval
specified in the SINEX file is equal or longer than the interval specified
by this option.

<p><i>Default value:</i> <tt>1&nbsp;day</tt>

<p><hr>

</body>
